\begin{remark}[What iter-047 does and does not do]
  Iter-047 \emph{generalises} the \v{C}ech complex / cohomology carriers from the structure sheaf to any sheaf of $k$-modules on $C$, and registers two \lstinline{rfl}-bridges to iter-012's specialisation. Iter-047 does \emph{not} construct any comparison map between $\mathtt{cechCohomology}$ and $\HModule'$, nor does it prove any vanishing of \v{C}ech cohomology. The actual substantive work is iter-048+:
  \begin{itemize}
    \item Iter-048 (Section~\ref{sec:moduleK_cech_acyclic_cover}): introduce \lstinline{class Scheme.IsCechAcyclicCover} (Čech-side positive-degree vanishing predicate) plus a consumer that takes the comparison map as an explicit hypothesis. This decouples Čech-side combinatorial vanishing from the substantive comparison theorem.
    \item Iter-049+ candidate: construct the comparison map $\mathtt{cechCohomology}\,(C)(F)(\mathcal U)(n) \to_{k} \HModule'\,k\,F\,n\,(\bigsqcup_i \mathcal U_i)$ and prove it is an iso under acyclicity hypotheses (substantive multi-iteration).
    \item Iter-050+ candidate (substantive multi-iteration): produce instances of $\IsCechAcyclicCover$ for basic-open covers of affine schemes (Serre's classical computation: the alternating-sum complex of localisations is exact in positive degrees).
    \item Iter-051 candidate: the producer instance $\IsAffineHModuleVanishing\,k\,C\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)$ chains iter-050+ Čech-side acyclicity with iter-049's comparison theorem and iter-048's consumer.
  \end{itemize}
\end{remark}

\section{\v{C}ech-side acyclicity carrier (iter-048)}
\label{sec:moduleK_cech_acyclic_cover}

Iter-048 introduces the \v{C}ech-side carrier predicate $\IsCechAcyclicCover$ that captures positive-degree vanishing of the parameterised \v{C}ech cohomology of Section~\ref{sec:moduleK_cech_parameterised}. This is the \v{C}ech-side combinatorial input that the iter-051+ producer instance for $\IsAffineHModuleVanishing\,k\,C\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)$ will consume. Iter-048 also packages an immediate consumer that, given the carrier hypothesis \emph{and} a comparison iso $\mathtt{cechCohomology} \simeq \HModule'$ on the cover supremum (passed as an explicit argument), transports the \v{C}ech-side vanishing to derived-side $\HModule'$ vanishing.

The design choice of taking the comparison iso as an \emph{explicit argument} (not a class field) is deliberate. The comparison theorem itself --- that for an acyclic cover the \v{C}ech complex computes derived-functor cohomology --- is the substantive iter-049+ work that Mathlib does not provide. By decoupling the \v{C}ech-side combinatorial vanishing (iter-048) from the comparison theorem (iter-049+), each lands as a single foundational iteration: iter-048's consumer becomes a pure transport once iter-049 furnishes the comparison theorem to plug in as the \lstinline{compIso} argument.

\begin{definition}[\v{C}ech-side acyclicity carrier predicate]
  \label{def:Scheme_IsCechAcyclicCover}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.IsCechAcyclicCover}
  \uses{def:Scheme_cechCohomology}
  Let $k$ be a field, $C : \Over\,(\Spec\,(\CommRingCat\,k))$, $F : \Sheaf\,(\opens\,C.\mathtt{left}.\mathtt{toTopCat})\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$ a sheaf of $k$-modules on $C$, and $\mathcal U : \iota \to \opens\,C.\mathtt{left}.\mathtt{toTopCat}$ an indexed family of opens. The cover $\mathcal U$ is \emph{\v{C}ech-acyclic for $F$} if $\mathtt{cechCohomology}\,(C)(F)(\mathcal U)(n)$ is a $\mathtt{Subsingleton}$ for every $n \ge 1$. Formally, this is captured by the single-field class
  \[
    \mathtt{class\,IsCechAcyclicCover}\,(F)(\mathcal U) : \mathrm{Prop}\;\text{where}\;\mathtt{subsingleton\_cechCohomology} : \forall (n : \mathbb N),\,0 < n \to \mathtt{Subsingleton}\,(\mathtt{cechCohomology}\,(C)(F)(\mathcal U)(n)).
  \]
\end{definition}

\begin{remark}[Why $\mathtt{Subsingleton}$ and not $\IsZero$]
  $\mathtt{cechCohomology}\,(C)(F)(\mathcal U)(n)$ has type $\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k$, which is a category-theoretic object. The vanishing of $\HModule'$ in the iter-040 carrier was packaged as $\mathtt{Subsingleton}$ because $\HModule'$ has $\mathtt{Type}$-flavour. Here $\mathtt{cechCohomology}$ has $\ModuleCat$-flavour but $\mathtt{Subsingleton}$ on the underlying type still works (one can use $\IsZero$ at the categorical level too, and the two are interchangeable for $\ModuleCat$). Choosing $\mathtt{Subsingleton}$ keeps the predicate uniform with iter-040 / iter-043 and makes the consumer's $\Module.\mathrm{Finite}$ chain work via the same $\mathtt{Subsingleton} \to \Module.\mathrm{Finite}$ instance synthesis path.
\end{remark}

\begin{theorem}[Subsingleton transport via \v{C}ech acyclicity + comparison]
  \label{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule'_supr_of_isCechAcyclicCover}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.subsingleton_HModule'_supr_of_isCechAcyclicCover}
  \uses{def:Scheme_IsCechAcyclicCover, def:Scheme_HModule'}
